### Cultivation System

1830-1870

- Each Villagse was forced to dedicate 20% of its land to growing and cultivating cash corps
- They can only sell the corps to the dutch at low, fixed prices (insufficient wage)

The remaining 80% of land was highly taxed by the government.

-> farms were producing lesser rice and more cash corps, 
**Fall in Staple corps production coupled with rising population mainly because of immigration**
-> FAMINE Caused

This system brought hardship to the javanese people

The Local elittsts, known as the bupati, collabed with the dutch gov and benefitied from the profits earned, even holding positions in colonial service

The chinese and arab immigrants became *tax farmers*, collect tax from people, and benefit from profit.

-> The dutch sold the cash corps for huge profit, and the netherlands came back from the brink if bankruptcy..

#### Reasons for cultivation system

-> Econ exploit, pay back for the cost of war

Development of agricultural system -> Increase exports ->Increase profits

Subsistence Farming -> Commercial farming (Terrace farming and irrigation farming, maximise yields)

### Abolishment of liberal policy (1870)


Aims:
- Replace the exploitive cultivation system
- Set-up private enterprises
- End dutch Monopoly on various cash corps
- Improve lives of peasents who ~~survived~~ Suffered, bring in econ reform
**Real aim: establish socio-political stability to attract EU investors to set up plantations or factories.. For the $(profits).**

#### Agrarian law
Allow private enterprises and individuals to lease land for 75 years from gov. to grow corps ofc.\
Private companies set-up, own and run plantation estates


#### Sugar law
Abolish sugar cultivation over 12 years(1878)
- Enable sugar plantations on the outer islands
- Remove govt monopoly of cash corps (pepper and spices) \<You can sell  the cash corps to others\>
